{
  "id": "G-S10-005-no-deadline-drift-across-drains",
  "rule": "G-S10",
  "description": "Deadline stability across drains: a calendar-snapped deadline must be identical whether computed on drain 1 or drain 2. Timer duration P3D from epoch has a naive deadline Sunday 1970-01-04; with a Monday holiday the calendar snaps it to Tuesday 1970-01-06 09:00 UTC (464,400,000 ms). A P1D delay forces a first drain that persists the snapped deadline. A second delay (P4DT9H) advances the clock to exactly 464,400,000 ms and the timer fires. With the pre-fix subtraction trick the second drain would recompute start as snapped_deadline - duration = 205,200,000 ms, shifting the business deadline forward and either missing the fire or placing it at the wrong time. With the fix (created_at_ms = 0) the recomputed deadline is identical across both drains.",
  "documents": {
    "kernel": "inline",
    "businessCalendar": "inline"
  },
